termination, and Canadian Citizenship -- tV The Right to Rural Policy -- t13 Density Matters and Distance Matters: Canadian Public Policy from a Rural Perspective -- t14 Rural Citizenship Under the Impact of Rural Transformation: Unpacking the Role of Spatial Planning in Protecting the Right to Be Rural in Zimbabwe -- t15 The Right to Multiple Futures in the Shadow of Canada’s Smart City Movement -- t16 “What Makes Our Land Illegal?” Regularization and the Urbanization of Rural Land in Ethiopia -- tVI The Right to Rural Mobility -- t17 Exploring Rural Citizenship through Displacement: An Analysis of Citizenship in the Context of Refugee Resettlement and Integration in Rural Canada -- t18 Local Politics of Inclusion and Exclusion: Exploring the Situation of Migrant Labourers and their Descendants after Land Reform in Rural Zimbabwe -- t19 Rural Redlining in the Danish Housing Market: Toward an Analytical Framework for Understanding Spatial (In)justice -- t20 What’s Next for the Right to Be Rural? -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this collection, researchers analyze rural societies, economies, and governance in North America, Europe, Africa, and Asia through the lens of rights and citizenship, across such varied domains as education, employment, and health. The provocative concept of a “right to be rural” illuminates not only the challenges faced by rural communities worldwide, but also underappreciated facets of community resilience in the face of these challenges. The book’s central question—“is there a right to be rural?”—offers insights into how these communities are created, maintained, and challenged. The authors illustrate that citizenship rights have a spatial character, and that this observation is critical to studying and understanding rural life in the twenty-first century. Scholars and policymakers concerned with the health and well-being of rural communities will be interested in this book. Contributors: Ray Bollman, Clement Chipenda, Innocent Chirisa, Logan Cochrane, Pallavi Das, Laura Domingo-Peñafiel, Laura Farré-Riera, Jens Kaae Fisker, Karen R. Foster, Lesley Frank, Greg Hadley, Stacey Haugen, Jennifer Jarman, Kathleen Kevany, Eshetayehu Kinfu, Al Lauzon, Katie MacLeod, Jeofrey Matai, Ilona Matysiak, Kayla McCarney, Rachel McLay, Egon Noe, Howard Ramos, Katja Rinne-Koski, Sulevi Riukulehto, Sarah Rudrum, Ario Seto, Nuria Simo-Gil, Peggy Smith, Sara Teitelbaum, Annette Aagaard Thuesen, Tom Tom, Ashleigh Weeden, Satenia Zimmermann  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aSocial Sciences / Rural Studies. 4aSocial Sciences. 4aSociology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Rural.2bisacsh  acapitalism.  acitizenship.  aeconomic development.  aeconomy.  aeducation.  aenvironment.  ageography.  ahuman rights.  aresistance.  arural governance.  asociology.  asustainability.1 aBollman, Ray D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBollman, Ray, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChipenda, Clement, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChirisa, Innocent, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCochrane, Logan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDas, Pallavi V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDas, Pallavi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDomingo-Peñafiel, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFarré-Riera, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFisker, Jens Kaae, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFoster, Karen R., e